      • fib

        public int fib(int n)
        This is the fibonacci algorithm which will be used to show excessive recomputation. With each recursive call e.g fib(8) then fib(6) and fib(7) is calculated. After the recursion n will then be 7 and will be returning fib(5) and fib(6). As you can see there is an overlap here where fib(6) is being calculated for a second time. This happens several times, with several calculations needlessly being recalculated and wasting processing time on calculations we should already have the result for.
        Specified by:
        fib in interface IExcessiveRecomp
        Parameters:
        n - Any integer greater than 0 and less than 11.
        Returns:
        Returns the value of the nth fibonacci number
        Since:
        1.0

      • fibMemoization

        public int fibMemoization(int n)
        This code is based on and sourced from: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/7875380/recursive-fibonacci-memoization%20 This is just an example of how excessive recomputation can be solved by storing results of already computed calculations to prevent them being calculated again. Instead the value is already known and simply fetched, in this case from the helperMemory array.
        Specified by:
        fibMemoization in interface IExcessiveRecomp
        Parameters:
        n - Any integer greater than 1 and less than 10.
        Returns:
        Returns the value of the nth fibonacci number
        Since:
        1.0
